1
00:01:58,093 --> 00:02:00,368
Quit eyeballing me, Flavius.

2
00:02:00,613 --> 00:02:03,685
I knew you when you was
a two-bit hustler on Bull Street.

3
00:02:48,893 --> 00:02:51,043
Excuse me!
Where can a fella get a cab?

4
00:02:51,293 --> 00:02:52,282
He just left.

5
00:02:52,533 --> 00:02:55,047
You can call the company, but I's you,
I'd wait on him to come back.

6
00:02:55,293 --> 00:02:56,931
'Less you want to take a ride.

7
00:02:57,173 --> 00:02:59,050
- You going to Jones Street?
- I'll get you there.

8
00:02:59,773 --> 00:03:01,047
Put your stuff in there.

9
00:03:06,053 --> 00:03:08,408
To your right. Pirate's House...

10
00:03:08,653 --> 00:03:10,928
...built in 1794.

11
00:03:11,173 --> 00:03:14,961
All the ne'er-do-wells and scalawags
divided up their booty there.

12
00:03:16,693 --> 00:03:18,888
Sherman stayed
in the Green-Meldrim House...

13
00:03:19,133 --> 00:03:21,931
...to rest up
after his fiery march through Atlanta.

14
00:03:22,173 --> 00:03:23,811
He was going to burn Savannah...

15
00:03:24,053 --> 00:03:27,045
...but the locals drowned him
in Chatham Artillery punch...

16
00:03:27,293 --> 00:03:29,602
...and fancy parties
till he decided...

17
00:03:29,853 --> 00:03:31,684
...to spare our fair city.

18
00:03:31,933 --> 00:03:34,163
Forsyth Park. Ladies and gentlemen.

19
00:03:58,933 --> 00:04:00,366
You looking for something?

20
00:04:02,253 --> 00:04:03,208
No.

21
00:04:26,013 --> 00:04:27,128
Mr. Kelso?

22
00:04:27,373 --> 00:04:29,204
Are you Mr. Kelso?

23
00:04:29,533 --> 00:04:32,809
I'm Lorene Baxter.
Welcome to Savannah.

24
00:04:33,533 --> 00:04:36,730
Town & Country
is my favorite magazine.

25
00:04:37,253 --> 00:04:41,007
Oh, my land, where are my manners?
What can I get you to drink?

26
00:04:41,973 --> 00:04:43,691
Anything cold would be great.

27
00:04:49,733 --> 00:04:51,883
Mr. Williams restored this home.

28
00:04:52,133 --> 00:04:54,931
One of the many he saved
from the wrecking ball.

29
00:04:57,413 --> 00:05:00,132
The carriage house is reserved
for Jim's clients...

30
00:05:00,373 --> 00:05:02,807
...and guests, such as yourself.

31
00:05:13,093 --> 00:05:14,287
He's here.

32
00:05:17,093 --> 00:05:19,402
Welcome, Mr. Kelsy.

33
00:05:19,733 --> 00:05:22,486
- I'm sorry, Mr. Kelso?
- John Kelso.

34
00:05:22,733 --> 00:05:24,564
Yes. I'm Betty Harty.

35
00:05:24,813 --> 00:05:26,326
Sonny's been expecting you.

36
00:05:26,573 --> 00:05:28,484
I'm here to see Jim Williams.

37
00:05:28,733 --> 00:05:30,610
Sonny's Jim's attorney.

38
00:05:34,893 --> 00:05:36,167
Well, hell...

39
00:05:36,413 --> 00:05:37,732
...come on in, coach.

40
00:05:38,333 --> 00:05:39,288
John Kelso.

41
00:05:40,413 --> 00:05:43,450
Welcome to the old curiosity shop.
Take a seat.

42
00:05:51,813 --> 00:05:53,724
You let me know.

43
00:05:56,653 --> 00:05:58,848
- How was your trip?
- Fine. Mr. Williams said...

44
00:05:59,093 --> 00:06:03,052
He will be right along. We have
a little business to attend to first.

45
00:06:03,293 --> 00:06:06,763
Confidentiality agreement.
Just boilerplate stuff.

46
00:06:07,013 --> 00:06:08,332
Plus a paragraph...

47
00:06:08,613 --> 00:06:11,491
...outlining Jim's editorial privileges.

48
00:06:12,933 --> 00:06:17,085
Town & Country flew me down to write
a 500-word story on a Christmas party.

49
00:06:17,333 --> 00:06:19,927
It's a literary postcard.
Are you serious about this?

50
00:06:20,493 --> 00:06:22,165
It's not just any party.

51
00:06:24,173 --> 00:06:25,686
Have you asked the magazine?

52
00:06:25,933 --> 00:06:28,766
I'd rather have your word
than some New York lawyer.

53
00:06:30,493 --> 00:06:32,211
Be that as it may...

54
00:06:33,013 --> 00:06:34,731
...I'm not going to sign that.

55
00:06:35,933 --> 00:06:37,571
Damn! How come?

56
00:06:38,333 --> 00:06:40,244
It's just a little old party write-up.

57
00:06:40,693 --> 00:06:42,809
All the more reason
not to compromise my ethics.

58
00:06:43,053 --> 00:06:45,851
As a professional,
I'm sure you understand.

59
00:06:50,893 --> 00:06:52,292
Promise to be fair?

60
00:06:52,813 --> 00:06:54,531
Yes, of course.

61
00:07:02,733 --> 00:07:03,643
Jim...

62
00:07:05,133 --> 00:07:06,851
...this is John Kelso.

63
00:07:07,133 --> 00:07:08,168
Hello.

64
00:07:09,853 --> 00:07:11,923
Let's take a walk,
shall we, sport?

65
00:07:15,933 --> 00:07:18,083
We'll go around Forsyth Park.

66
00:07:29,373 --> 00:07:30,647
Would y'all mind...?

67
00:07:30,893 --> 00:07:32,531
Not at all, Betty.

68
00:07:33,573 --> 00:07:34,528
Come on.

69
00:07:41,773 --> 00:07:43,331
Did you sign Sonny's papers?

70
00:07:43,653 --> 00:07:44,768
Actually, no.

71
00:07:45,933 --> 00:07:49,892
Good for you. Sonny's
overly protective of my interests.

72
00:07:50,493 --> 00:07:52,643
- Still walking the dog, Mr. Glover?
- Yes, sir.

73
00:07:52,893 --> 00:07:55,248
Patrick do love his morning walk.

74
00:08:00,773 --> 00:08:03,845
Would you mind? Could I please have
my picture made with Uga?

75
00:08:04,253 --> 00:08:05,208
Great.

76
00:08:05,493 --> 00:08:06,528
Thanks.

77
00:08:08,333 --> 00:08:10,005
All right. Smile.

78
00:08:12,213 --> 00:08:13,931
Thanks. Dang good dog.

79
00:08:15,493 --> 00:08:16,403
Thank you very much.

80
00:08:16,693 --> 00:08:17,921
Thank you for asking.

81
00:08:19,373 --> 00:08:22,331
No matter what you and I ever do
in our lives, Mr. Kelso...

82
00:08:22,613 --> 00:08:24,729
...neither of us
will be as famous as Uga.

83
00:08:25,533 --> 00:08:26,602
He's the university mascot.

84
00:08:26,853 --> 00:08:28,684
- "The Georgia Bulldog."
- Is that right?

85
00:08:29,013 --> 00:08:32,926
I know I'm going to regret asking,
but that man said he was walking a dog.

86
00:08:34,813 --> 00:08:35,848
What dog?

87
00:08:36,133 --> 00:08:38,283
Mr. Glover was the law firm porter.

88
00:08:38,733 --> 00:08:42,851
Mr. Bouhan said in his will that
Mr. Glover should continue to be paid...

89
00:08:43,133 --> 00:08:46,250
...$ 15 every week for walking Patrick,
his Labrador.

90
00:08:46,573 --> 00:08:47,608
So...

91
00:08:48,453 --> 00:08:49,442
...where's Patrick?

92
00:08:49,733 --> 00:08:54,363
Patrick went on to his great rewards
2 years after Mr. Bouhan, about 1974.

93
00:08:54,653 --> 00:08:56,530
- The dog's dead.
- Quite.

94
00:08:57,613 --> 00:08:59,763
Why doesn't Mr. Glover walk Uga?

95
00:09:02,733 --> 00:09:04,610
Well, then, who'd walk Patrick?

96
00:09:08,293 --> 00:09:09,692
I see.

97
00:09:12,213 --> 00:09:14,169
- There it is.
- This is your house?

98
00:09:14,973 --> 00:09:18,932
Built by General Hugh Mercer in 1860,
but he never lived in this house.

99
00:09:19,213 --> 00:09:21,169
His great-grandson was Johnny Mercer.

100
00:09:21,453 --> 00:09:22,522
The songwriter?

101
00:09:22,813 --> 00:09:24,041
Savannah's own.

102
00:09:24,853 --> 00:09:26,684
What's your favorite of his tunes?

103
00:09:27,373 --> 00:09:30,251
My mother was always partial
to "Fools Rush In."

104
00:09:30,653 --> 00:09:31,802
Your mother.

105
00:09:32,613 --> 00:09:33,489
Indeed.

106
00:09:33,893 --> 00:09:38,683
I'd love to give you the grand tour, but
they're still setting up for the party.

107
00:09:39,613 --> 00:09:41,444
I thought the party was tomorrow night.

108
00:09:41,733 --> 00:09:43,212
There are two parties.

109
00:09:43,453 --> 00:09:46,411
Tonight is for bachelors.
Gentlemen only.

110
00:09:47,573 --> 00:09:48,688
Would you like to come?

111
00:09:49,853 --> 00:09:50,888
I'd like to cover it.

112
00:09:51,133 --> 00:09:54,284
I'm sorry. It's private.
Reporters aren't allowed.

113
00:09:54,533 --> 00:09:57,525
Would you like to see my shop?
It's back here in the carriage house.

114
00:10:00,013 --> 00:10:04,689
This house is one of the largest
in Savannah. It covers an entire block.

115
00:10:04,973 --> 00:10:06,326
It's right in here.

116
00:10:06,613 --> 00:10:08,444
This is where we do all of our...

117
00:10:08,693 --> 00:10:10,172
...restorations.

118
00:10:21,733 --> 00:10:23,564
This landscape, is it a Stubbs?

119
00:10:24,253 --> 00:10:25,402
Very good.

120
00:10:26,013 --> 00:10:27,446
My father was a dealer.

121
00:10:27,693 --> 00:10:30,730
It's called Newmarket Heath
with a Rubbing-Down House.

122
00:10:30,973 --> 00:10:33,646
It's a recent purchase I will unveil
at tomorrow night's event.

123
00:10:34,053 --> 00:10:35,566
It's an odd piece.

124
00:10:36,173 --> 00:10:37,891
The impasto is interesting.

125
00:10:38,933 --> 00:10:40,002
Where's your black light?

126
00:10:49,813 --> 00:10:50,768
It's an overpaint.

127
00:10:51,573 --> 00:10:53,245
Very good, sport.

128
00:10:57,573 --> 00:10:59,564
- You had it x-rayed yet?
- No.

129
00:11:00,493 --> 00:11:02,245
How will you know
what it's obscuring?

130
00:11:04,053 --> 00:11:05,884
I rather enjoy not knowing.

131
00:12:02,013 --> 00:12:03,207
Just a minute.

132
00:12:11,053 --> 00:12:12,691
- Who is it?
- Mandy.

133
00:12:12,973 --> 00:12:13,849
Who?

134
00:12:15,733 --> 00:12:16,882
I don't know a Mandy.

135
00:12:17,133 --> 00:12:19,601
Of course not.
You won't open the damn door.

136
00:12:21,293 --> 00:12:23,170
Hi. Nice to meet you.

137
00:12:31,653 --> 00:12:33,564
You all got some ice?

138
00:12:35,853 --> 00:12:37,172
Sure, help yourself.

139
00:12:37,653 --> 00:12:40,725
Joe Odom's fridge is on the blink.
And plus, at present...

140
00:12:40,973 --> 00:12:43,043
...we don't have electricity.

141
00:12:44,973 --> 00:12:46,247
Thirsty?

142
00:12:47,293 --> 00:12:49,443
Me? No.
No, not really.

143
00:12:51,213 --> 00:12:55,206
If you're thirsty, a drink'll cure it.
If you're not, a drink'll prevent it.

144
00:12:55,493 --> 00:12:57,802
Prevention is better than a cure.

145
00:13:00,653 --> 00:13:02,609
Put on some pants, John Kelso.

146
00:13:05,133 --> 00:13:06,646
Sure, just let me get a pair.

147
00:13:09,453 --> 00:13:12,331
This is our newest addition
to the Odom House.

148
00:13:12,653 --> 00:13:15,963
As you see, Joe's been creative
with our electrical dilemma.

149
00:13:18,453 --> 00:13:22,082
I done this before
and I ain't never been killed yet.

150
00:13:22,333 --> 00:13:24,722
But there's a first time for everything.

151
00:13:32,133 --> 00:13:33,009
There we go!

152
00:13:33,253 --> 00:13:34,447
We got it!

153
00:13:35,653 --> 00:13:36,563
No problem.

154
00:13:37,013 --> 00:13:38,082
Joe Odom?

155
00:13:38,333 --> 00:13:39,561
The one, the only.

156
00:13:39,933 --> 00:13:41,286
Where's my libation?

157
00:13:41,573 --> 00:13:42,403
Hold these.

158
00:13:44,133 --> 00:13:46,328
To Savannah Electric and Power!

159
00:13:46,973 --> 00:13:49,282
And let's not forget our friends...

160
00:13:49,853 --> 00:13:50,763
...the...

161
00:13:51,213 --> 00:13:51,929
...whoever!

162
00:13:53,453 --> 00:13:55,762
Here's to you!
All right, inside.

163
00:13:56,773 --> 00:14:01,130
Honey, that's a tough job,
but you're talking to the lady. Hello!

164
00:14:02,173 --> 00:14:05,006
Have you met Mr. Kelso,
our newest addition to Savannah?

165
00:14:05,293 --> 00:14:06,612
Jerry Spence.

166
00:14:06,853 --> 00:14:08,571
- How are you?
- I'm charmed now.

167
00:14:08,853 --> 00:14:10,969
- How are you?
- I'm pretty good.

168
00:14:11,213 --> 00:14:13,329
- I wonder if he goes to my church?
- I wonder.

169
00:14:13,653 --> 00:14:14,642
Episcopalian.

170
00:14:14,893 --> 00:14:16,087
We'll find out.

171
00:14:16,333 --> 00:14:17,561
Sanitation

172
00:14:18,173 --> 00:14:20,733
I see all night long
Hauling in great big cans

173
00:14:23,013 --> 00:14:26,244
I'm hoping one day soon
She'll let me be a Hefty man

174
00:14:27,693 --> 00:14:30,082
In the Dumpster
We'll be making love

175
00:14:30,333 --> 00:14:32,483
In the Dumpster
Beneath the stars above

176
00:14:32,813 --> 00:14:35,168
In the Dumpster
I smell paradise

177
00:14:35,453 --> 00:14:37,284
Don 't have to ask me twice

178
00:14:37,573 --> 00:14:39,529
It's all I'm thinking of

179
00:14:39,773 --> 00:14:42,333
Just me and that trash girl
Making that Dumpster love

180
00:14:54,573 --> 00:14:55,449
Do you like that?

181
00:14:55,693 --> 00:14:56,842
Strong.

182
00:14:57,213 --> 00:14:59,886
Strong and good.
Chatham Artillery punch.

183
00:15:00,173 --> 00:15:01,128
What's in it?

184
00:15:01,373 --> 00:15:03,091
3 parts fruit, 7 parts liquor.

185
00:15:03,373 --> 00:15:05,329
Whatever's available on both counts.

186
00:15:05,653 --> 00:15:07,291
Great party. Great house.

187
00:15:08,333 --> 00:15:12,690
The fella that owns it is in Europe
for a year. Asked me to look in on it.

188
00:15:12,973 --> 00:15:14,292
Water the plants.

189
00:15:17,573 --> 00:15:18,369
Squatting?

190
00:15:19,733 --> 00:15:21,485
That's a vicious word.

191
00:15:21,813 --> 00:15:23,451
You're not a lawyer, are you?

192
00:15:25,133 --> 00:15:28,205
Good. They're the scum of the earth.
And I should know...

193
00:15:28,493 --> 00:15:31,053
...being an ex-barrister myself.

194
00:15:31,453 --> 00:15:32,408
Ex?

195
00:15:33,053 --> 00:15:36,204
Ceremoniously disbarred
not two years ago.

196
00:15:36,493 --> 00:15:38,370
Had a little accounting snafu.

197
00:15:38,973 --> 00:15:40,201
What do you do now?

198
00:15:40,453 --> 00:15:43,251
Me and Mandy,
we're going to open a piano bar.

199
00:15:43,573 --> 00:15:44,608
You already have one.

200
00:15:44,853 --> 00:15:46,332
Looks that way, doesn't it?

201
00:15:46,853 --> 00:15:49,003
Wait a minute. Hold the music.

202
00:15:49,293 --> 00:15:50,169
Look.

203
00:15:52,093 --> 00:15:53,321
Look at this.

204
00:15:53,653 --> 00:15:54,722
Jerry Spence.

205
00:15:55,893 --> 00:15:58,612
You have outdone yourself again.

206
00:15:58,853 --> 00:16:02,448
That is a coif definitely befitting
your stature as the future ex...

207
00:16:02,773 --> 00:16:04,172
...Mrs. Joe Odom.

208
00:16:04,893 --> 00:16:06,611
Keep dreaming, darling.

209
00:16:07,013 --> 00:16:08,207
You're in love.

210
00:16:11,813 --> 00:16:13,804
She is one beautiful woman.

211
00:16:14,173 --> 00:16:15,572
You two engaged?

212
00:16:16,773 --> 00:16:17,842
Not yet.

213
00:16:19,573 --> 00:16:22,645
It's getting late. I'm going to
hit the road. Nice meeting you.

214
00:16:22,893 --> 00:16:24,246
No, wait a minute.

215
00:16:25,133 --> 00:16:26,771
Joe's rule #2:

216
00:16:27,053 --> 00:16:31,046
If you have to leave a party,
you always take a traveler.

217
00:16:32,013 --> 00:16:34,402
I can live with that one.
Nice to meet you.

218
00:16:41,733 --> 00:16:42,722
Hey, there.

219
00:16:43,653 --> 00:16:46,167
Better to be on the edge of a party,
don't you think?

220
00:16:48,413 --> 00:16:49,687
Thanks for inviting me.

221
00:16:49,933 --> 00:16:50,968
Anytime.

222
00:16:51,213 --> 00:16:52,487
Every time.

223
00:16:58,893 --> 00:17:00,008
Earlier...

224
00:17:00,253 --> 00:17:01,572
...how'd you know my name?

225
00:17:01,853 --> 00:17:03,445
Welcome to Savannah.

226
00:17:11,213 --> 00:17:12,328
Mr. John Kelso?

227
00:17:14,413 --> 00:17:15,368
This is for you.

228
00:17:23,373 --> 00:17:26,683
I'm not in. Leave a message
and I'll get back to you.

229
00:17:46,813 --> 00:17:48,371
- Mr. Kelso?
- Yes.

230
00:17:48,613 --> 00:17:51,207
I'm Lucille Wright.
I cater Mr. Williams' parties.

231
00:17:51,453 --> 00:17:53,171
- Nice to meet you.
- He'll be down shortly.

232
00:17:53,413 --> 00:17:55,165
Would you like to see what we'll serve?

233
00:17:55,413 --> 00:17:56,607
Of course.

234
00:17:56,853 --> 00:17:57,922
Come in.

235
00:18:00,213 --> 00:18:02,488
Lots of fresh vegetables...

236
00:18:02,733 --> 00:18:04,291
...hot bread...

237
00:18:04,533 --> 00:18:05,932
...jumbo shrimp.

238
00:18:07,533 --> 00:18:10,127
Let's see.
This is smoked ham and turkey.

239
00:18:10,733 --> 00:18:11,449
Both.

240
00:18:11,693 --> 00:18:15,652
A big fruit platter.
And this is a wonderful crab dish.

241
00:18:15,893 --> 00:18:16,803
A bisque?

242
00:18:17,373 --> 00:18:18,123
Jeff Braswell.

243
00:18:19,733 --> 00:18:23,009
- I shoot Jim's parties.
- Let's get a shot of the whole spread.

244
00:18:23,253 --> 00:18:25,642
Town & Country
loves its pretty pictures.

245
00:18:26,133 --> 00:18:28,089
And pumpkin cornbread.

246
00:18:29,453 --> 00:18:33,002
Mr. Williams insists on
low-country cooking for his parties.

247
00:18:33,493 --> 00:18:36,291
Oh, you're going to have fun tonight.

248
00:18:36,533 --> 00:18:38,285
Indeed he is, Lucille.

249
00:18:39,413 --> 00:18:41,722
Good fit. 44 long.

250
00:18:45,333 --> 00:18:47,608
I have an eye for framing things.

251
00:18:49,933 --> 00:18:51,924
Welcome to Mercer House, Mr. Kelso.

252
00:18:52,853 --> 00:18:55,242
You have outdone yourself again
this year.

253
00:18:55,493 --> 00:18:56,972
Well, thank you.

254
00:19:31,573 --> 00:19:32,926
I'm glad to see you.
Merry Christmas.

255
00:19:33,293 --> 00:19:34,646
Merry Christmas.

256
00:19:34,893 --> 00:19:38,363
There you are. The man with the cigar.
So happy you're back.

257
00:19:39,093 --> 00:19:40,048
Emma.

258
00:19:41,613 --> 00:19:44,207
Did you watch my drink for me?
Merry Christmas.

259
00:19:44,453 --> 00:19:46,808
I thought you'd tried
to steal it from me.

260
00:19:47,333 --> 00:19:48,925
